<div class="courseblock main">
<p class="courseblocktitle"><strong>RLST 21430.  Religion and American Capitalism.  100 Units.</strong></p><p class="courseblockdesc">
This course will introduce students to the intersection of religion and capitalism in the United States. Through a variety of primary and secondary readings, we will explore how religious people and institutions have interacted with, affirmed, and challenged American capitalism. We will pay particularly close attention to the alternative moral economics envisioned by religious communities in the United States.</p><p class="courseblockdetail">
Instructor(s): William Schultz     Terms Offered: Autumn<br/>
Note(s): This course meets the HS Committee distribution requirement for Divinity students.<br/>
Equivalent Course(s): HIST 37716, AMER 40200, AMER 21430, RAME 40200, HIST 27716, HCHR 40200<br/>
</p>
