<div class="courseblock main">
<p class="courseblocktitle"><strong>RLST 28590.  Sandworms, Spice, and Spirituality: Religion in Frank Herbert's Dune.  100 Units.</strong></p><p class="courseblockdesc">
Dune is widely considered a masterpiece of science fiction, and the success of its recent film adaptation attests to its continuing appeal. Yet in addition to its characters and worldbuilding, Dune also offers insightful portrayals of religion and explores religion's roles in society and culture. How do a community's ecological, economic, and political contexts shape their religious beliefs? In what ways do beliefs change or develop over time? Why are rituals such important parts of religious systems? How do stories about &quot;salvation&quot; and the &quot;end times&quot; shape communal identity, purpose, and behavior? In this course, we will ponder these and other questions by placing Dune in conversation with the Qur'an, the Bible, and other religious texts to see how the same dynamics are at play. No prior reading or knowledge of the novel required.</p><p class="courseblockdetail">
Instructor(s): Doug Hoffer     Terms Offered: Winter<br/>
</p>
